Title: The Jungle Book
Credit: Written by
Author: Rudyard Kipling
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Period live-action jungle adventure; talking beasts of the Seeonee share one naturalistic medium—fur, muscle, and breath, not cartoon. Warm India nights, moon on stone, fire as terror. Anthology of the jungle's peoples under one Law.

===

EXT. SEEONEE HILLS - NIGHT

Moon over teak and grass. A warm wind. Far off, a kite wheels home.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Now Rann the Kite brings home the night that Mang the Bat sets free. The herds are shut in byre and hut—for loosed till dawn are we. This is the hour of pride and power, talon and tush and claw. Oh, hear the call!—Good hunting all that keep the Jungle Law!

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

A cave mouth open to moonlight. FATHER WOLF—lean, scarred gray timber wolf—wakes from day's rest, scratches, yawns, spreads his paws one after another.

MOTHER WOLF (RAKSHA)—big gray nose, fierce eyes—lies with four tumbling, squealing CUBS against her flank.

FATHER WOLF
Augrh! It is time to hunt again.

He gathers to spring downhill. A little shadow with a bushy tail crosses the threshold and whines—TABAQUI the jackal, mean, grinning, dish-licker.

TABAQUI
Good luck go with you, O Chief of the Wolves. And good luck and strong white teeth go with noble children that they may never forget the hungry in this world.

Father Wolf stiffens. The cubs squeal. Mother Wolf's ears flatten.

FATHER WOLF
Enter, then, and look—but there is no food here.

TABAQUI
For a wolf, no. But for so mean a person as myself a dry bone is a good feast. Who are we, the Gidur-log, to pick and choose?

He scuttles to the back, finds a buck bone with meat, cracks it merrily.

TABAQUI
All thanks for this good meal. How beautiful are the noble children! How large are their eyes! And so young too! Indeed, indeed, I might have remembered that the children of kings are men from the beginning.

Mother and Father Wolf look uncomfortable. Tabaqui rejoices in the mischief.

TABAQUI
(spitefully)
Shere Khan, the Big One, has shifted his hunting grounds. He will hunt among these hills for the next moon, so he has told me.

FATHER WOLF
He has no right! By the Law of the Jungle he has no right to change his quarters without due warning. He will frighten every head of game within ten miles, and I—I have to kill for two, these days.

MOTHER WOLF
His mother did not call him Lungri for nothing. He has been lame in one foot from his birth. That is why he has only killed cattle. Now the villagers of the Waingunga are angry with him, and he has come here to make our villagers angry. They will scour the jungle for him when he is far away, and we and our children must run when the grass is set alight. Indeed, we are very grateful to Shere Khan!

TABAQUI
Shall I tell him of your gratitude?

FATHER WOLF
Out! Out and hunt with thy master. Thou hast done harm enough for one night.

TABAQUI
I go. Ye can hear Shere Khan below in the thickets. I might have saved myself the message.

He slips out.

EXT. VALLEY BELOW THE CAVE - NIGHT

Below, toward a little river: the dry, angry, snarly, singsong whine of a tiger who has caught nothing.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

Father Wolf listens at the mouth.

FATHER WOLF
The fool! To begin a night's work with that noise! Does he think that our buck are like his fat Waingunga bullocks?

MOTHER WOLF
H'sh. It is neither bullock nor buck he hunts to-night. It is Man.

The whine changes to a humming purr from every quarter—the sound that bewilders woodcutters in the open.

FATHER WOLF
(showing white teeth)
Man! Faugh! Are there not enough beetles and frogs in the tanks that he must eat Man, and on our ground too!

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The Law of the Jungle forbids every beast to eat Man except when he is killing to show his children how to kill. Man-killing means, sooner or later, white men on elephants, with guns—and then everybody in the jungle suffers.

The purr ends in a full-throated tiger's charge—then an untigerish howl.

MOTHER WOLF
He has missed. What is it?

EXT. SCRUB BELOW THE CAVE - NIGHT

FATHER WOLF runs out a few paces. SHERE KHAN—great lame tiger, shoulders huge, one forefoot spoiled—tumbles and mutters in the scrub. Tabaqui dances near him. A woodcutter's campfire glows; the tiger's pads are burned.

FATHER WOLF (O.S.)
The fool has had no more sense than to jump at a woodcutter's campfire, and has burned his feet. Tabaqui is with him.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

MOTHER WOLF
Something is coming uphill. Get ready.

Bushes rustle. Father Wolf drops, haunches under him, ready to leap—then checks in mid-spring, shoots straight up four or five feet, lands almost where he left ground.

FATHER WOLF
Man! A man's cub. Look!

Directly in front of him, holding a low branch: a naked brown BABY who can just walk—soft, dimpled. He looks up into Father Wolf's face and laughs.

MOTHER WOLF
Is that a man's cub? I have never seen one. Bring it here.

Father Wolf mouths the child as gently as an egg, jaws on the back, not a scratch, and lays him among the cubs.

MOTHER WOLF
How little! How naked, and—how bold!

The baby pushes between the cubs toward the warm hide.

MOTHER WOLF
Ahai! He is taking his meal with the others. And so this is a man's cub. Now, was there ever a wolf that could boast of a man's cub among her children?

FATHER WOLF
I have heard now and again of such a thing, but never in our Pack or in my time. He is altogether without hair, and I could kill him with a touch of my foot. But see, he looks up and is not afraid.

Moonlight blocks out. SHERE KHAN's great square head and shoulders thrust into the entrance—cramped, too big for the mouth. Tabaqui squeaks behind.

TABAQUI
My lord, my lord, it went in here!

FATHER WOLF
(eyes angry)
Shere Khan does us great honor. What does Shere Khan need?

SHERE KHAN
My quarry. A man's cub went this way. Its parents have run off. Give it to me.

FATHER WOLF
The Wolves are a free people. They take orders from the Head of the Pack, and not from any striped cattle-killer. The man's cub is ours—to kill if we choose.

SHERE KHAN
Ye choose and ye do not choose! What talk is this of choosing? By the bull that I killed, am I to stand nosing into your dog's den for my fair dues? It is I, Shere Khan, who speak!

His roar fills the cave with thunder. Mother Wolf shakes free of the cubs and springs forward—eyes like two green moons facing his blaze.

MOTHER WOLF
And it is I, Raksha, who answers. The man's cub is mine, Lungri—mine to me! He shall not be killed. He shall live to run with the Pack and to hunt with the Pack; and in the end, look you, hunter of little naked cubs—frog-eater—fish-killer—he shall hunt thee! Now get hence, or by the Sambhur that I killed, back thou goest to thy mother, burned beast of the jungle, lamer than ever thou camest into the world! Go!

Shere Khan backs out growling. Clear of the mouth, he shouts:

SHERE KHAN
Each dog barks in his own yard! We will see what the Pack will say to this fostering of man-cubs. The cub is mine, and to my teeth he will come in the end, O bush-tailed thieves!

Mother Wolf throws herself down panting among the cubs.

FATHER WOLF
Shere Khan speaks this much truth. The cub must be shown to the Pack. Wilt thou still keep him, Mother?

MOTHER WOLF
Keep him! He came naked, by night, alone and very hungry; yet he was not afraid! Look, he has pushed one of my babes to one side already. And that lame butcher would have killed him and would have run off to the Waingunga while the villagers here hunted through all our lairs in revenge! Keep him? Assuredly I will keep him. Lie still, little frog. O thou Mowgli—for Mowgli the Frog I will call thee—the time will come when thou wilt hunt Shere Khan as he has hunted thee.

FATHER WOLF
But what will our Pack say?

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Full moon. A hilltop of stones and boulders. AKELA—great gray Lone Wolf—lies full length on his rock. Below, forty or more WOLVES of every size and color. Cubs tumble in the center. Seniors pad up, inspect, return on noiseless feet.

AKELA
Ye know the Law—ye know the Law. Look well, O Wolves!

ANXIOUS MOTHERS
Look—look well, O Wolves!

Father Wolf, Mother Wolf, their four cubs, and little MOWGLI. Father Wolf pushes Mowgli into the center. The boy sits laughing, playing with pebbles that glisten in the moonlight.

AKELA
(never raising his head)
Look well!

A muffled roar from behind the rocks—SHERE KHAN.

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
The cub is mine. Give him to me. What have the Free People to do with a man's cub?

AKELA
Look well, O Wolves! What have the Free People to do with the orders of any save the Free People? Look well!

A young wolf snarls. Others join. The Pack is divided.

BAGHEERA—inky black panther, moon-marks of water on his coat—drops into the circle as softly as ink poured from a bottle. BALOO the brown bear pushes up among the wolves.

BALOO
I speak for the man's cub. There is no harm in a man's cub. I have no gift of cattle or game to buy free passage, but I will teach him the Law of the Jungle. Let him run with the Pack. I myself will teach him.

BAGHEERA
O Akela, and ye the Free People, I have no right in your assembly; but the Law of the Jungle says that if there is a doubt which is not a killing matter in regard to a new cub, the life of that cub may be bought at a price. And the Law does not say who may or may not pay that price. Am I right?

AKELA
Good! Good! It is the Law. Now, a price indeed!

BAGHEERA
I will buy his life with a newly killed bull, and my word is known in the jungle.

The Pack howls acceptance. Shere Khan's roar fades down the hill.

AKELA
Look well, O Wolves!

Mowgli is accepted. Bagheera's eyes burn green as he looks toward the dark where Shere Khan went.

BAGHEERA
(softly)
Aye, roar well. For the time comes when this naked thing will make thee roar to another tune, or I know nothing of Man.

EXT. JUNGLE CLEARING - DAY

Years later. Sun filters through heavy green. BALOO sits like a boulder while young MOWGLI—lean, brown, bare—recites before him. BAGHEERA lounges against a tree-trunk, head pressed to the bark, purring.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It was in the days when Baloo was teaching him the Law of the Jungle. The young wolves learn only what touches their own pack—but a man-cub must learn a great deal more.

MOWGLI
Feet that make no noise; eyes that can see in the dark; ears that can hear the winds in their lairs, and sharp white teeth—

BALOO
Again. And the rest—except Tabaqui the Jackal and the Hyaena whom we hate.

Mowgli repeats, restless. Baloo cuffs him softly; the boy's cheek flushes. He bolts up a trunk in a temper. Bagheera's eyes narrow.

BAGHEERA
But think how small he is. How can his little head carry all thy long talk?

BALOO
Is there anything in the jungle too little to be killed? No. That is why I teach him these things, and that is why I hit him, very softly, when he forgets.

BAGHEERA
Softly! What dost thou know of softness, old Iron-feet? His face is all bruised today by thy—softness. Ugh.

BALOO
Better he should be bruised from head to foot by me who love him than that he should come to harm through ignorance. I am now teaching him the Master Words of the Jungle that shall protect him with the birds and the Snake People, and all that hunt on four feet, except his own pack. Is not that worth a little beating?

BAGHEERA
Well, look to it then that thou dost not kill the man-cub. He is no tree trunk to sharpen thy blunt claws upon. But what are those Master Words?

Baloo lifts his muzzle.

BALOO
Come, Little Brother!

A sullen voice from the leaves above.

MOWGLI
My head is ringing like a bee tree.

Mowgli slides down the trunk, angry, and plants himself before Bagheera.

MOWGLI
I come for Bagheera and not for thee, fat old Baloo!

BALOO
That is all one to me. Tell Bagheera, then, the Master Words of the Jungle that I have taught thee this day.

MOWGLI
Master Words for which people? The jungle has many tongues. I know them all.

BALOO
A little thou knowest, but not much. See, O Bagheera, they never thank their teacher. Say the word for the Hunting-People, then—great scholar.

MOWGLI
(Bear accent)
We be of one blood, ye and I.

BALOO
Good. Now for the birds.

Mowgli repeats it with a kite's whistle at the end.

BAGHEERA
Now for the Snake-People.

Mowgli answers with a long, perfect hiss. He kicks up his heels, claps, and vaults onto Bagheera's back, drumming the glossy hide and making faces at Baloo.

BALOO
There—there! That was worth a little bruise. Some day thou wilt remember me.

Baloo turns to Bagheera, proud, patting his furry stomach.

BALOO
Hathi the Wild Elephant gave me the Words. Mowgli is reasonably safe against all accidents in the jungle. No one then is to be feared.

BAGHEERA
(under his breath)
Except his own tribe.
(aloud)
Have a care for my ribs, Little Brother! What is all this dancing up and down?

Mowgli pulls Bagheera's shoulder-fur, shouting.

MOWGLI
And so I shall have a tribe of my own, and lead them through the branches all day long.

BAGHEERA
What is this new folly, little dreamer of dreams?

MOWGLI
Yes, and throw branches and dirt at old Baloo. They have promised me this. Ah!

Baloo's big paw scoops Mowgli off the panther. The boy lies between the bear's forepaws. Baloo's face is dark.

BALOO
Mowgli, thou hast been talking with the Bandar-log—the Monkey People.

Bagheera's eyes go hard as jade. Mowgli glances from one to the other.

BAGHEERA
Thou hast been with the Monkey People—the gray apes—the people without a law—the eaters of everything. That is great shame.

MOWGLI
When Baloo hurt my head, I went away, and the gray apes came down from the trees and had pity on me. No one else cared.

BALOO
The pity of the Monkey People! The stillness of the mountain stream! The cool of the summer sun! And then, man-cub?

MOWGLI
And then they gave me nuts and pleasant things to eat, and they carried me in their arms up to the top of the trees and said I was their blood brother except that I had no tail, and should be their leader some day.

BAGHEERA
They have no leader. They lie. They have always lied.

MOWGLI
They were very kind and bade me come again. Why have I never been taken among the Monkey People? They stand on their feet as I do. They do not hit me with their hard paws. They play all day. Let me get up! Bad Baloo, let me up! I will play with them again.

Baloo's voice rumbles like thunder on a hot night. The forest stills.

BALOO
Listen, man-cub. I have taught thee all the Law of the Jungle for all the peoples of the jungle—except the Monkey-Folk who live in the trees. They have no law. They are outcasts. They have no speech of their own, but use the stolen words which they overhear when they listen, and peep, and wait up above in the branches. Their way is not our way. They are without leaders. They have no remembrance. They boast and chatter and pretend that they are a great people about to do great affairs in the jungle, but the falling of a nut turns their minds to laughter and all is forgotten. We of the jungle have no dealings with them. We do not drink where the monkeys drink; we do not go where the monkeys go; we do not hunt where they hunt; we do not die where they die. Hast thou ever heard me speak of the Bandar-log till today?

MOWGLI
(whisper)
No.

BALOO
The Jungle-People put them out of their mouths and out of their minds. They are very many, evil, dirty, shameless, and they desire, if they have any fixed desire, to be noticed by the Jungle People. But we do not notice them even when they throw nuts and filth on our heads.

A shower of nuts and twigs spatters through the branches. High above: coughings, howlings, angry jumpings among the thin limbs. Gray shapes—the BANDAR-LOG—flicker and vanish.

BALOO
The Monkey-People are forbidden. Forbidden to the Jungle-People. Remember.

BAGHEERA
Forbidden, but I still think Baloo should have warned thee against them.

BALOO
I—I? How was I to guess he would play with such dirt. The Monkey People! Faugh!

A fresh shower. Baloo and Bagheera trot away, taking Mowgli with them.

EXT. JUNGLE UNDER BIG TREES - DAY

Midday heat. Mowgli sleeps ashamed between Bagheera and Baloo, resolving no more truck with monkeys. Hard little hands seize his legs and arms. Branches swash his face.

He is yanked upward. Baloo wakes the jungle with deep cries. Bagheera bounds up the trunk, every tooth bared. The Bandar-log howl with triumph and scuffle to the upper branches where the panther dare not follow.

BANDAR-LOG
He has noticed us! Bagheera has noticed us. All the Jungle-People admire us for our skill and our cunning.

Two strong monkeys catch Mowgli under the arms and swing off through the treetops, twenty feet at a bound. The whole tribe sweeps along the tree-roads—bounding, crashing, whooping—Mowgli their prisoner.

EXT. JUNGLE TREETOPS - DAY

The flight: roads and crossroads fifty to a hundred feet up. Mowgli's escort rushes him to thinning topmost branches that crackle and bend, then flings outward and down to the next tree. Glimpses of green miles; leaves lash his face; the jerk over empty air brings his heart between his teeth.

Sick and giddy, he still feels the wild rush. He stares upward into blue.

Far off, RANN THE KITE balances and wheels, watching the jungle. Rann drops a few hundred yards, whistles surprise at the man-cub.

Mowgli gives the Kite call.

MOWGLI
We be of one blood, thou and I!

Branches close; his brown face breaks up again.

MOWGLI
Mark my trail! Tell Baloo of the Seeonee Pack and Bagheera of the Council Rock.

RANN
In whose name, Brother?

MOWGLI
Mowgli, the Frog. Man-cub they call me! Mark my trail!

Shrieked as he is swung through air. Rann nods and rises till he is a speck, telescope eyes on the swaying treetops.

RANN
They never go far. They never do what they set out to do. Always pecking at new things are the Bandar-log. This time they have pecked down trouble for themselves.

He rocks on his wings and waits.

EXT. JUNGLE FLOOR - DAY

Bagheera climbs as never before; thin branches break; he slips down, claws full of bark. Baloo sets off at a clumsy trot.

BAGHEERA
Why didst thou not warn the man-cub? What was the use of half slaying him with blows if thou didst not warn him?

BALOO
Haste! O haste! We—we may catch them yet!

BAGHEERA
At that speed! It would not tire a wounded cow. Teacher of the Law—cub-beater—a mile an hour is no way to help a friend.

Baloo groans and flounders on. Rann stoops from the sky and cries the trail.

RANN
He has gone toward the Cold Lairs—the lost city. The Bandar-log have taken him there.

BAGHEERA
Then we need Kaa.

EXT. WARM ROCKS ABOVE THE RIVER - DAY

KAA—thirty feet of rock-python, newly changed coat dull and loose—lies half in sun, half in shadow. Bagheera and Baloo approach with respect.

BALOO
We be of one blood, ye and I.

KAA
What is this talk of blood? Has Baloo forgotten that he once told me I was black and muddy, and a meat-eater?

BAGHEERA
We seek aid. The Bandar-log have stolen our man-cub.

KAA
The Monkey-People? Footless, yellow earth-worms. Up, Baloo! They called me footless yellow earth-worm? They shall pay.

He glides after them toward the Cold Lairs.

EXT. COLD LAIRS - DUSK

Lost city of stone: terraces, cracked domes, a great tank of green water. Bandar-log throng the roofs and battlements, chattering. Mowgli is thrust into a ruined summer-house whose marble screen-work is too fine for a boy to climb.

INT. RUINED SUMMER-HOUSE - DUSK

COBRAS coil in the dust among the rubbish. Mowgli stands among them and gives the Master Word.

MOWGLI
We be of one blood, ye and I.

COBRAS
Even so. But stand still, Little Brother, for thy feet may do us harm.

EXT. COLD LAIRS TERRACE - NIGHT

Baloo and Bagheera burst among the monkeys. The fight is savage—monkeys swarm, bite, tear. Bagheera is driven into the tank. Baloo stands over him roaring, thick fur torn and bloody.

KAA arrives. He opens his mouth and speaks one long hissing word. Far-off monkey bands freeze on the loaded branches. The city falls still. BAGHEERA climbs the red steps from the tank, shaking his wet sides.

The clamor breaks out again—monkeys leap higher, cling to the necks of stone idols, shriek along the battlements. Inside the ruined summer-house, MOWGLI dances, eye to the screen-work, and hoots owl-fashion between his front teeth.

BAGHEERA
Get the man-cub out of that trap; I can do no more. Let us take the man-cub and go. They may attack again.

KAA
They will not move till I order them. Stay you sssso!

Silence clamps the city once more.

KAA
I could not come before, Brother, but I think I heard thee call.

BAGHEERA
I—I may have cried out in the battle. Baloo, art thou hurt?

BALOO
I am not sure that they did not pull me into a hundred little bearlings. Wow! I am sore. Kaa, we owe thee, I think, our lives—Bagheera and I.

KAA
No matter. Where is the manling?

MOWGLI (O.S.)
Here, in a trap. I cannot climb out.

INT. RUINED SUMMER-HOUSE - NIGHT

The curve of the broken dome hangs above MOWGLI's head. COBRAS coil in the dust among the rubbish.

COBRAS
Take him away. He dances like Mao the Peacock. He will crush our young.

EXT. COLD LAIRS TERRACE - NIGHT

KAA
Hah! He has friends everywhere, this manling. Stand back, manling. And hide you, O Poison People. I break down the wall.

KAA finds a discolored crack in the marble tracery. Two or three light taps for distance. Then six feet of body lift clear of the ground—half a dozen full-power smashing blows, nose-first.

The screen-work bursts inward in a cloud of dust and rubbish.

MOWGLI leaps through the opening and flings himself between BALOO and BAGHEERA—an arm around each big neck.

BALOO
Art thou hurt?

MOWGLI
I am sore, hungry, and not a little bruised. But, oh, they have handled ye grievously, my Brothers! Ye bleed.

BAGHEERA
Others also.

He licks his lips, looking at the monkey-dead on the terrace and round the tank.

BALOO
It is nothing, it is nothing, if thou art safe, oh, my pride of all little frogs!

BAGHEERA
Of that we shall judge later. But here is Kaa to whom we owe the battle and thou owest thy life. Thank him according to our customs, Mowgli.

MOWGLI turns. The great Python's head sways a foot above his own.

KAA
So this is the manling. Very soft is his skin, and he is not unlike the Bandar-log. Have a care, manling, that I do not mistake thee for a monkey some twilight when I have newly changed my coat.

MOWGLI
We be of one blood, thou and I. I take my life from thee tonight. My kill shall be thy kill if ever thou art hungry, O Kaa.

KAA
All thanks, Little Brother. And what may so bold a hunter kill? I ask that I may follow when next he goes abroad.

MOWGLI
I kill nothing,—I am too little,—but I drive goats toward such as can use them. When thou art empty come to me and see if I speak the truth. I have some skill in these—

He holds out his hands.

MOWGLI
—and if ever thou art in a trap, I may pay the debt which I owe to thee, to Bagheera, and to Baloo, here. Good hunting to ye all, my masters.

BALOO
Well said.

KAA drops his head lightly for a minute on MOWGLI's shoulder.

KAA
A brave heart and a courteous tongue. They shall carry thee far through the jungle, manling. But now go hence quickly with thy friends. Go and sleep, for the moon sets, and what follows it is not well that thou shouldst see.

The moon sinks behind the hills. Lines of trembling monkeys huddle on the walls like ragged shaky fringes. BALOO goes down to the tank for a drink. BAGHEERA puts his fur in order.

KAA glides into the center of the terrace and brings his jaws together with a ringing snap. Every monkey eye fixes on him.

KAA
The moon sets. Is there yet light enough to see?

BANDAR-LOG
We see, O Kaa.

KAA
Good. Begins now the dance—the Dance of the Hunger of Kaa. Sit still and watch.

He turns twice or thrice in a big circle, weaving his head from right to left. Loops and figures of eight; soft oozy triangles that melt into squares and five-sided figures and coiled mounds—never resting, never hurrying. A low humming song. Darker and darker till the coils disappear; only the rustle of scales remains.

BALOO and BAGHEERA stand still as stone, growling in their throats, neck hair bristling. MOWGLI watches and wonders.

KAA
Bandar-log, can ye stir foot or hand without my order? Speak!

BANDAR-LOG
Without thy order we cannot stir foot or hand, O Kaa!

KAA
Good! Come all one pace nearer to me.

The lines of monkeys sway forward helplessly. BALOO and BAGHEERA take one stiff step with them.

KAA
Nearer!

They all move again.

MOWGLI lays his hands on BALOO and BAGHEERA. The two great beasts start as though waked from a dream.

BAGHEERA
Keep thy hand on my shoulder. Keep it there, or I must go back—must go back to Kaa. Aah!

MOWGLI
It is only old Kaa making circles on the dust. Let us go.

The three slip off through a gap in the walls toward the jungle. Behind them the rustle and the humming song go on.

EXT. JUNGLE OUTSIDE COLD LAIRS - NIGHT

Under the still trees, BALOO shakes himself all over.

BALOO
Whoof! Never more will I make an ally of Kaa.

BAGHEERA
He knows more than we. In a little time, had I stayed, I should have walked down his throat.

BALOO
Many will walk by that road before the moon rises again. He will have good hunting—after his own fashion.

MOWGLI
But what was the meaning of it all? I saw no more than a big snake making foolish circles till the dark came. And his nose was all sore. Ho! Ho!

BAGHEERA
Mowgli, his nose was sore on thy account, as my ears and sides and paws, and Baloo's neck and shoulders are bitten on thy account. Neither Baloo nor Bagheera will be able to hunt with pleasure for many days.

BALOO
It is nothing; we have the man-cub again.

BAGHEERA
True, but he has cost us heavily in time which might have been spent in good hunting, in wounds, in hair—I am half plucked along my back—and last of all, in honor. For, remember, Mowgli, I, who am the Black Panther, was forced to call upon Kaa for protection, and Baloo and I were both made stupid as little birds by the Hunger Dance. All this, man-cub, came of thy playing with the Bandar-log.

MOWGLI
True, it is true. I am an evil man-cub, and my stomach is sad in me.

BAGHEERA
Mf! What says the Law of the Jungle, Baloo?

BALOO
Sorrow never stays punishment. But remember, Bagheera, he is very little.

BAGHEERA
I will remember. But he has done mischief, and blows must be dealt now. Mowgli, hast thou anything to say?

MOWGLI
Nothing. I did wrong. Baloo and thou art wounded. It is just.

BAGHEERA gives him half a dozen love-taps—from a panther's point of view light enough for his own cubs; for a seven-year-old boy, a beating hard to wish for. When it is over MOWGLI sneezes and picks himself up without a word.

BAGHEERA
Now, jump on my back, Little Brother, and we will go home.

MOWGLI lays his head down on BAGHEERA's back and sleeps so deeply he does not wake when he is set down in the home-cave. Punishment has settled the score. No nagging afterward.

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Years later. Akela is old. The Pack has grown bold and lawless. Shere Khan has been among the younger wolves with honeyed words. Mowgli—taller, scarred, a knife at his side from the village edge—stands in the circle. Bagheera crouches near.

AKELA
Free People, ye have eaten my food and slept in my lair. Ye have said I was no longer fit to lead. Is it so?

Young wolves howl him down. Shere Khan's voice from the dark:

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
He is a man. Drive him out! Kill him!

BAGHEERA
Open thy mouth, Little Brother. The Red Flower.

Mowgli steps into the firelight with a blazing branch—the Red Flower stolen from the village. Wolves shrink. Shere Khan flinches from the heat.

MOWGLI
Good hunting to you all, my masters. Free People, ye have cast me out. I go. But first—

He lays the branch at Shere Khan's feet. The tiger snarls and backs.

MOWGLI
Up, dog! Up, when a man speaks, or I will set thy hide ablaze!

The Pack scatters. Mowgli turns to Mother Wolf at the cave mouth.

MOWGLI
I go from you to my own people—if they be my own people. The jungle is shut to me.

MOTHER WOLF
Come soon, little naked son of mine. For, listen, child of man, I loved thee more than ever I loved my cubs.

MOWGLI
I will surely come back. And when I come it will be to lay out Shere Khan's hide upon the Council Rock. Do not forget me! Tell them in the jungle never to forget me!

He walks away down the hill with the Red Flower, alone.

EXT. VALLEY ROAD - DAY

Sun on rough track. MOWGLI—long hair, white scars on arms and legs, barefoot—jogs at a steady pace down the valley. Behind him, the jungle. Ahead, country he does not know.

Nearly twenty miles at the jog-trot.

EXT. GREAT PLAIN - DAY

The valley opens into a plain dotted with rocks and cut by ravines. At one end a little village; at the other the thick jungle sweeps down to the grazing-grounds and stops as if cut with a hoe. Cattle and buffaloes graze. Herd-boys shout and run. Yellow pariah dogs bark.

MOWGLI walks on, hungry.

EXT. VILLAGE GATE - DAY

A big thorn-bush barricade has been pushed aside for the day.

MOWGLI
Umph. So men are afraid of the People of the Jungle here also.

He sits by the gate. A MAN comes out. MOWGLI stands, opens his mouth, points down it—food. The man stares and runs back up the single street shouting.

The PRIEST arrives—big, fat, dressed in white, a red and yellow mark on his forehead—and with him at least a hundred people who stare and talk and point.

MOWGLI throws back his long hair and frowns.

MOWGLI
(to himself)
They have no manners, these Men Folk. Only the gray ape would behave as they do.

MESSUA—kind-eyed village woman—pushes through.

MESSUA
Nathoo! Nathoo! My son that was taken by the tiger!

She takes Mowgli's hands. The Priest claims a miracle and a hundred rupees. Messua leads Mowgli home.

INT. MESSUA'S HUT - NIGHT

Messua feeds him milk and bread, cuts his hair, gives him a cloth. Mowgli endures it, half wild, half grateful.

MESSUA
Sleep, little son. In the morning we will see.

EXT. VILLAGE GRAZING-GROUNDS - DAY

Weeks pass. Mowgli learns to herd buffaloes with GRAY BROTHER watching from the jungle edge. BULDEO the village hunter boasts under the peepul tree of his tiger kills—always Shere Khan just missed.

GRAY BROTHER slips to Mowgli among the herd.

GRAY BROTHER
Shere Khan has come back to this country to kill thee. He lies up now in the big dry ravine of the Waingunga.

MOWGLI
I am not afraid. Take word to Akela. We will need the herd.

EXT. RAVINE MOUTH - DAY

Hot noon. Mowgli divides the buffalo herd—cows and calves one way with Gray Brother, the big bulls with Akela the other. He himself rides the great herd-bull RAMA.

SHERE KHAN wakes in the ravine from a full meal of village cattle, heavy and slow. The two wings of the herd close like gates. No way out but the steep sides.

MOWGLI
Herd! Herd! Drive!

Buffaloes thunder into the ravine. Dust. Roars. The lame tiger is caught under the charge. When the herd pours out the far end, Shere Khan lies dead, trampled into the mud.

MOWGLI drops from Rama's neck. With his knife he works long and carefully, skinning the great striped hide while kites circle.

GRAY BROTHER
It is done. Take the skin to Council Rock as thou didst promise.

EXT. VILLAGE GATE - TWILIGHT

Mowgli comes toward the village with the hide on his head. Buldeo meets him on the road, greedy for the reward on Shere Khan.

BULDEO
That skin is mine. A boy does not kill the Tiger.

Mowgli laughs. Gray Brother shows himself. Buldeo flees, screaming witchcraft.

At the gate, stones fly. A young buffalo bellows, hit by BULDEO's shot. The crowd presses the gate.

VILLAGERS
More sorcery! He can turn bullets. Buldeo, that was thy buffalo.

MOWGLI stands bewildered as brickbats whistle past.

MOWGLI
Now what is this?

AKELA sits down composedly beside the herd.

AKELA
They are not unlike the Pack, these brothers of thine. It is in my head that, if bullets mean anything, they would cast thee out.

The PRIEST waves a sprig of sacred tulsi plant.

PRIEST
Wolf! Wolf's cub! Go away!

MOWGLI
Again? Last time it was because I was a man. This time it is because I am a wolf. Let us go, Akela.

MESSUA breaks from the crowd and runs across to the herd.

MESSUA
Oh, my son, my son! They say thou art a sorcerer who can turn himself into a beast at will. I do not believe, but go away or they will kill thee. Buldeo says thou art a wizard, but I know thou hast avenged Nathoo's death.

VILLAGERS
Come back, Messua! Come back, or we will stone thee.

A stone hits MOWGLI in the mouth. He laughs a short, ugly laugh. Blood on his lip.

MOWGLI
Run back, Messua. This is one of the foolish tales they tell under the big tree at dusk. I have at least paid for thy son's life. Farewell; and run quickly, for I shall send the herd in more swiftly than their brickbats. I am no wizard, Messua. Farewell!

MESSUA hesitates, then flees back toward the houses.

MOWGLI
Now, once more, Akela. Bring the herd in.

AKELA's yell cracks across the plain. The buffaloes, anxious for home, need little urging. They charge through the gate like a whirlwind, scattering VILLAGERS right and left.

MOWGLI
(scornfully)
Keep count! It may be that I have stolen one of them. Keep count, for I will do your herding no more. Fare you well, children of men, and thank Messua that I do not come in with my wolves and hunt you up and down your street.

He turns on his heel and walks away with AKELA into the darkening plain.

EXT. PLAIN BY THE RAVINE - NIGHT

Moonrise. The plain looks milky white. MOWGLI trots at a steady wolf's pace, a bundled hide balanced on his head. GRAY BROTHER and AKELA run at his heels.

MOWGLI
No more sleeping in traps for me, Akela. Let us get Shere Khan's skin and go away. No, we will not hurt the village, for Messua was kind to me.

Behind them, far off, temple bells bang and conches blare. He looks up at the stars and almost smiles.

EXT. VILLAGE GATE - NIGHT

MESSUA weeps against the gate-post. BULDEO holds court among the GRAY-BEARDS and VILLAGERS, arms wide, embroidering.

BULDEO
—and Akela stood up on his hind legs and talked like a man!

The bells and conches grow louder, drowning him.

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT

Moon almost down. MOWGLI, AKELA, and GRAY BROTHER climb the hill and stop at the mouth of Mother Wolf's cave. MOWGLI still bears the rolled hide.

MOWGLI
They have cast me out from the Man-Pack, Mother, but I come with the hide of Shere Khan to keep my word.

MOTHER WOLF walks stiffly from the cave, the remaining CUBS behind her. Her eyes glow as she sees the striped skin.

MOTHER WOLF
I told him on that day, when he crammed his head and shoulders into this cave, hunting for thy life, Little Frog—I told him that the hunter would be the hunted. It is well done.

A deep purr from the thicket. BAGHEERA bounds into the open and runs to MOWGLI's bare feet.

BAGHEERA
Little Brother, it is well done. We were lonely in the jungle without thee.

They clamber up the Council Rock together. MOWGLI spreads SHERE KHAN's skin on the flat stone where AKELA used to sit. He pegs it down with four slivers of bamboo. AKELA lies down upon it.

AKELA
Look—look well, O Wolves!

The old call rolls into the jungle.

Wolves answer from habit. They limp in—lame from traps, shot-wounded, mangy from bad food. Many places in the circle empty. All that are left of the Pack gather and stare at the striped hide, huge claws dangling from the empty feet.

MOWGLI leaps onto the rattling skin. A song rises in his throat. He shouts it, beating time with his heels, dancing till breath fails. GRAY BROTHER and AKELA howl between the verses.

MOWGLI
The Song of Mowgli—I, Mowgli, am singing. Let the jungle listen to the things I have done.

Shere Khan said he would kill—would kill! At the gates in the twilight he would kill Mowgli, the Frog!

He ate and he drank. Drink deep, Shere Khan, for when wilt thou drink again? Sleep and dream of the kill.

I am alone on the grazing-grounds. Gray Brother, come to me! Come to me, Lone Wolf, for there is big game afoot!

Bring up the great bull buffaloes, the blue-skinned herd bulls with the angry eyes. Drive them to and fro as I order.

Sleepest thou still, Shere Khan? Wake, oh, wake! Here come I, and the bulls are behind.

Rama, the King of the Buffaloes, stamped with his foot. Waters of the Waingunga, whither went Shere Khan?

He is not Ikki to dig holes, nor Mao, the Peacock, that he should fly. He is not Mang the Bat, to hang in the branches. Little bamboos that creak together, tell me where he ran?

Ow! He is there. Ahoo! He is there. Under the feet of Rama lies the Lame One! Up, Shere Khan!

Up and kill! Here is meat; break the necks of the bulls!

Hsh! He is asleep. We will not wake him, for his strength is very great. The kites have come down to see it. The black ants have come up to know it. There is a great assembly in his honor.

Alala! I have no cloth to wrap me. The kites will see that I am naked. I am ashamed to meet all these people.

Lend me thy coat, Shere Khan. Lend me thy gay striped coat that I may go to the Council Rock.

By the Bull that bought me I made a promise—a little promise. Only thy coat is lacking before I keep my word.

With the knife, with the knife that men use, with the knife of the hunter, I will stoop down for my gift.

Waters of the Waingunga, Shere Khan gives me his coat for the love that he bears me. Pull, Gray Brother! Pull, Akela! Heavy is the hide of Shere Khan.

The Man Pack are angry. They throw stones and talk child's talk. My mouth is bleeding. Let me run away.

Through the night, through the hot night, run swiftly with me, my brothers. We will leave the lights of the village and go to the low moon.

Waters of the Waingunga, the Man-Pack have cast me out. I did them no harm, but they were afraid of me. Why?

Wolf Pack, ye have cast me out too. The jungle is shut to me and the village gates are shut. Why?

As Mang flies between the beasts and birds, so fly I between the village and the jungle. Why?

I dance on the hide of Shere Khan, but my heart is very heavy. My mouth is cut and wounded with the stones from the village, but my heart is very light, because I have come back to the jungle. Why?

These two things fight together in me as the snakes fight in the spring. The water comes out of my eyes; yet I laugh while it falls. Why?

I am two Mowglis, but the hide of Shere Khan is under my feet.

All the jungle knows that I have killed Shere Khan. Look—look well, O Wolves!

Ahae! My heart is heavy with the things that I do not understand.

He stands panting on the hide. Tears and blood on his face.

MOWGLI
Look well, O Wolves. Have I kept my word?

The Pack bays yes. One tattered wolf shoulders forward.

TATTERED WOLF
Lead us again, O Akela. Lead us again, O Man-cub, for we be sick of this lawlessness, and we would be the Free People once more.

BAGHEERA
Nay, that may not be. When ye are full-fed, the madness may come upon you again. Not for nothing are ye called the Free People. Ye fought for freedom, and it is yours. Eat it, O Wolves.

MOWGLI
Man-Pack and Wolf-Pack have cast me out. Now I will hunt alone in the jungle.

GRAY BROTHER
And we will hunt with thee.

The four CUBS press against his legs. MOWGLI looks once more at the hide, at MOTHER WOLF, at BAGHEERA—then turns toward the dark trees.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And that is the last of the Mowgli tales in this book. But the jungle holds other stories, and other peoples under the Law—or outside it.

EXT. STEAMER DECK - NIGHT

Fog and cold spray. A tiny winter wren—LIMMERSHIN—clings exhausted to the rigging. A hand reaches; he is carried below.

INT. STEAMER CABIN - NIGHT

Warm lamp light. LIMMERSHIN hops on a berth edge, feathers drying, crumbs before him. Beyond the porthole, black Bering water.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Limmershin, the Winter Wren, told me the tale when he was blown on to the rigging of a steamer going to Japan. He knows how to tell the truth.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Gray sea, basalt rock, endless fog. Hundreds of thousands of fur seals pack the shore—fighting, bellowing, crawling. From Hutchinson's Hill the nurseries stretch more than three miles. Surf dotted with seal heads.

SEA CATCH—great scarred fighting seal—hauls out and roars for his place. MATKAH his wife swims in the swell. Between them a newborn pup, white as snow—KOTICK.

MATKAH
He is white! All white!

SEA CATCH
Never mind the color. He is mine. Good hunting, little scrapper.

Years blur: Kotick grows, still pure white, mocked by the holluschickie. He swims farther than any seal of his year.

EXT. SEA OFF THE PRIBILOFS - DAY

Sealers' boats. Clubs rise and fall on the beaches. Kotick sees the killing—rows of skins, the Salt House, the waste. He swims from sea to sea seeking a place men have never found.

EXT. UNDERSEA CLIFF TUNNEL - DAY

Years of search. At last the SEA COWS—huge, lazy, gentle—lead him through a long black tunnel under the cliffs.

EXT. SAFE BEACHES BEYOND THE TUNNEL - DAY

KOTICK bursts up gasping and puffing into open water at the farther end, mane streaming.

KOTICK
My wig! It was a long dive, but it was worth it.

The SEA COWS have separated and browse lazily along the edges of the finest beaches he has ever seen. Long stretches of smooth-worn rock run for miles, fitted for seal-nurseries. Hard sand playgrounds slope inland. Rollers break for dancing. Long grass. Sand dunes. Beautiful rolling fog.

KOTICK feels the water with his whole body—no men have ever come here.

He tests the fishing, then swims the beaches, counting low sandy islands half hidden in the fog. Away northward, bars and shoals and rocks that would never let a ship within six miles. Between the islands and the mainland, deep water runs up to perpendicular cliffs. Somewhere below those cliffs: the tunnel mouth.

KOTICK
It's Novastoshnah over again, but ten times better. Sea Cow must be wiser than I thought. Men can't come down the cliffs, even if there were any men; and the shoals to seaward would knock a ship to splinters. If any place in the sea is safe, this is it.

He thoroughly explores so he can answer all questions—then dives, finds the tunnel mouth again, and races south.

EXT. UNDERSEA CLIFF TUNNEL - DAY

Black water. KOTICK drives through the long dark, chest burning, and is gone toward home.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Six days later. KOTICK hauls out just above Sea Lion's Neck.

The first person he meets is SHE-SEAL, who has been waiting. She sees by the look in his eyes that he has found his island at last.

HOLLOSCHICKIE SEAL, SEA CATCH, and the other seals crowd round as he tells them. They laugh.

YOUNG SEAL, about Kotick's age, twists his head from side to side. He has just married that year and makes a great fuss about it.

YOUNG SEAL
This is all very well, Kotick, but you can't come from no one knows where and order us off like this. Remember we've been fighting for our nurseries, and that's a thing you never did. You preferred prowling about in the sea.

The other seals laugh. YOUNG SEAL preens.

KOTICK
I've no nursery to fight for. I only want to show you all a place where you will be safe. What's the use of fighting?

YOUNG SEAL
(with an ugly chuckle)
Oh, if you're trying to back out, of course I've no more to say.

A green light comes into KOTICK's eye.

KOTICK
Will you come with me if I win?

YOUNG SEAL
(carelessly)
Very good. If you win, I'll come.

He has no time to change his mind. KOTICK's head is out; teeth sink in the blubber of the young seal's neck. KOTICK throws himself back on his haunches, hauls his enemy down the beach, shakes him, knocks him over.

KOTICK
(roaring to the seals)
I've done my best for you these five seasons past. I've found you the island where you'll be safe, but unless your heads are dragged off your silly necks you won't believe. I'm going to teach you now. Look out for yourselves!

He flings himself at the biggest sea catch he can find—catches him by the throat, chokes, bumps, bangs him till the old fighter grunts for mercy—throws him aside and attacks the next.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Never in all his little life did Limmershin see anything like Kotick's charge into the nurseries. Kotick had never fasted four months as the big seals did every year. His deep-sea swimming kept him in perfect condition. And he had never fought before.

KOTICK's curly white mane stands up with rage. Eyes flame. Big dog-teeth glisten. He is splendid.

SEA CATCH sees him tearing past, hauling grizzled old seals about as though they were halibut, upsetting young bachelors in all directions.

SEA CATCH
(roaring)
He may be a fool, but he is the best fighter on the beaches! Don't tackle your father, my son! He's with you!

KOTICK roars in answer. Old SEA CATCH waddles in, mustache on end, blowing like a locomotive.

MATKAH and SHE-SEAL cower down and admire their men-folk.

It is a gorgeous fight. Father and son fight as long as any seal dares lift up his head. When none remain, they parade grandly up and down the beach side by side, bellowing.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - NIGHT

Northern Lights wink and flash through the fog.

KOTICK climbs a bare rock and looks down on the scattered nurseries and the torn and bleeding seals.

KOTICK
Now. I've taught you your lesson.

SEA CATCH boosts himself up stiffly, fearfully mauled.

SEA CATCH
My wig! The Killer Whale himself could not have cut them up worse. Son, I'm proud of you, and what's more, I'll come with you to your island—if there is such a place.

KOTICK
(roaring)
Hear you, fat pigs of the sea. Who comes with me to the Sea Cow's tunnel? Answer, or I shall teach you again!

A murmur like the ripple of the tide all up and down the beaches.

SEALS
(thousands of tired voices)
We will come. We will follow Kotick, the White Seal.

KOTICK drops his head between his shoulders and shuts his eyes proudly. He is not a white seal any more, but red from head to tail. He scorns to look at or touch one of his wounds.

EXT. SEA OFF NOVASTOSHNAH - DAY

A week later. KOTICK leads his army—nearly ten thousand holluschickie and old seals—away north toward the Sea Cow's tunnel.

On the beach behind, the seals that stay call them idiots.

EXT. SAFE BEACHES BEYOND THE TUNNEL - DAY

Year after year, more seals leave Novastoshnah and Lukannon and the other nurseries for the quiet sheltered beaches.

KOTICK sits all the summer through, getting bigger and fatter and stronger, while the holluschickie play around him in that sea where no man comes.

EXT. OPEN SEA - DAY

Seals stream through the swell, heading back toward beaches in summer. Their voices rise—a great deep-sea song, sad as a national anthem.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I met my mates in the morning (and, oh, but I am old!)
Where roaring on the ledges the summer ground-swell rolled;
I heard them lift the chorus that drowned the breakers' song—
The Beaches of Lukannon—two million voices strong.

The song of pleasant stations beside the salt lagoons,
The song of blowing squadrons that shuffled down the dunes,
The song of midnight dances that churned the sea to flame—
The Beaches of Lukannon—before the sealers came!

I met my mates in the morning (I'll never meet them more!);
They came and went in legions that darkened all the shore.
And o'er the foam-flecked offing as far as voice could reach
We hailed the landing-parties and we sang them up the beach.

The Beaches of Lukannon—the winter wheat so tall—
The dripping, crinkled lichens, and the sea-fog drenching all!
The platforms of our playground, all shining smooth and worn!
The Beaches of Lukannon—the home where we were born!

I met my mates in the morning, a broken, scattered band.
Men shoot us in the water and club us on the land;
Men drive us to the Salt House like silly sheep and tame,
And still we sing Lukannon—before the sealers came.

Wheel down, wheel down to southward; oh, Gooverooska, go!
And tell the Deep-Sea Viceroys the story of our woe;
Ere, empty as the shark's egg the tempest flings ashore,
The Beaches of Lukannon shall know their sons no more!

EXT. ROADSIDE DITCH - DAY

A high summer flood. Brown water tears along the ditch.

A small mongoose—RIKKI-TIKKI, rather like a little cat in fur and tail, quite like a weasel in head and habits, eyes and restless nose pink—is washed kicking and clucking out of his burrow. He clings to a wisp of floating grass till he loses his senses.

EXT. GARDEN PATH - DAY

Hot sun. RIKKI-TIKKI lies draggled on the middle of a garden path.

TEDDY, a small English boy, stands over him.

TEDDY
Here's a dead mongoose. Let's have a funeral.

ALICE
(his mother)
No, let's take him in and dry him. Perhaps he isn't really dead.

They carry him toward the bungalow.

INT. BUNGALOW SITTING ROOM - DAY

TEDDY'S FATHER, a big Englishman, picks RIKKI-TIKKI up between finger and thumb.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Not dead. Half choked.

They wrap the mongoose in cotton wool and warm him over a little fire. RIKKI-TIKKI opens his eyes and sneezes.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Now, don't frighten him, and we'll see what he'll do.

RIKKI-TIKKI looks at the cotton wool, decides it is not good to eat, runs all round the table, sits up and puts his fur in order, scratches himself, and jumps on TEDDY's shoulder.

TEDDY'S FATHER
Don't be frightened, Teddy. That's his way of making friends.

TEDDY
Ouch! He's tickling under my chin.

RIKKI-TIKKI snuffs at the boy's ear, climbs down, sits rubbing his nose.

ALICE
Good gracious, and that's a wild creature! I suppose he's so tame because we've been kind to him.

TEDDY'S FATHER
All mongooses are like that. If he doesn't do any mischief we shall give him something to eat.

They give him raw meat. Rikki-tikki sleeps in Teddy's room that night and every night after.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Rikki explores. DARZEE the tailor-bird and DARZEE'S WIFE cry from a thorn-bush—a fledgling eaten by NAG the cobra.

RIKKI-TIKKI
Who is Nag?

NAG—five feet of cobra, spectacles on his hood—rises from the grass.

NAG
I am Nag. Look, and be afraid!

Rikki bristles but holds his ground. From the garden path NAGAINA, Nag's wicked wife, strikes at him from behind. Rikki leaps aside, bites, and is gone into the roses.

INT. BATHROOM - NIGHT

Rikki hears a dry crawl on the bricks. Nag has come to the water-jar to wait for Teddy's father at bathing-time—to kill the man and clear the bungalow for cobras.

RIKKI-TIKKI
(softly)
If I fight him here I shall be crushed. But if I let him go he will kill.

He springs and locks on Nag's head behind the hood. Man and wife wake to the thrashing. Teddy's father fires his shotgun. Nag lies dead. Rikki, half deaf, half drowned, is praised and fed.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Nagaina mourns and plots. She means to kill the family and avenge Nag. Darzee's wife pretends a broken wing and lures her from the melon-bed where the cobra eggs lie.

Rikki smashes egg after egg—soft and white—until one remains. Nagaina returns in fury.

NAGAINA
Give me the last of my eggs, and I will go. Give it and be still!

She seizes the egg and races for the rat-hole under the wall. Rikki follows into the dark.

Long silence. Then Rikki crawls out alone, dusty, triumphant.

RIKKI-TIKKI
It is all over.

INT. TEDDY'S NURSERY - NIGHT

RIKKI-TIKKI blinks up from TEDDY's shoulder. ALICE stands in the doorway; TEDDY'S FATHER behind her.

RIKKI-TIKKI
Oh, it's you. What are you bothering for? All the cobras are dead. And if they weren't, I'm here.

He settles again, proud but not swollen with it, and sleeps.

EXT. BUNGALOW GARDEN - DAY

Sun on the roses and the thorn-bush. RIKKI-TIKKI patrols the paths with tooth and jump and spring and bite. Never a cobra head shows inside the walls.

In the thorn-bush, DARZEE the tailor-bird fluffs and sings, wings half-spread. DARZEE'S WIFE listens from the nest.

DARZEE
Singer and tailor am I—
Doubled the joys that I know—
Proud of my lilt to the sky,
Proud of the house that I sew—
Over and under, so weave I my music—so weave I the house that I sew.

Sing to your fledglings again,
Mother, oh lift up your head!
Evil that plagued us is slain,
Death in the garden lies dead.
Terror that hid in the roses is impotent—flung on the dung-hill and dead!

Who has delivered us, who?
Tell me his nest and his name.
Rikki, the valiant, the true,
Tikki, with eyeballs of flame,
Rikk-tikki-tikki, the ivory-fanged, the hunter with eyeballs of flame!

Give him the Thanks of the Birds,
Bowing with tail feathers spread!
Praise him with nightingale words—
Nay, I will praise him instead.
Hear! I will sing you the praise of the bottle-tailed Rikki, with eyeballs of red!

RIKKI-TIKKI pops up under the bush, impatient.

RIKKI-TIKKI
That's enough, Darzee.

The rest of the song is lost. RIKKI-TIKKI trots on through the safe garden.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
So the bungalow garden was kept as a mongoose should keep it.

EXT. GARRO HILLS - DAY

Mist and teak forest. Far below, a river glints. A line of working elephants moves along a ridge path—great gray backs, copper-banded tusk-stumps, mahouts on their necks.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Kala Nag, which means Black Snake, had served the Indian Government in every way that an elephant could serve it for forty-seven years. Caught at twenty, he was nearly seventy—a ripe age for an elephant.

EXT. TIMBER YARD / MARCH ROAD - DAY

Quick flashes under NARRATOR: KALA NAG, a huge bull ten fair feet at the shoulder, tusks cut short and bound with copper bands, pushes a gun out of mud with a leather pad on his forehead; is hoisted by steam crane onto a ship; carries a mortar in rocky country; hauls teak balks; hammers a shirking young elephant into line.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had seen shell-fire and the dead Emperor at Magdala, cold and sunstroke at Ali Musjid, and the timber-yards at Moulmein. He gave up being afraid before he was twenty-five—and so became the best-loved elephant in the service.

EXT. KEDDAH STOCKADE - NIGHT

Torchlight. A big drop-gate of lashed tree trunks jars down. Wild elephants scream and crash inside the stockade. KALA NAG goes in at the word of command into the flaring pandemonium, picks the biggest tusker, hammers and hustles him quiet while men on other elephants rope the smaller ones.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
There was nothing in the way of fighting that Kala Nag did not know.

EXT. ELEPHANT CAMP CLEARING - DAY

KALA NAG stands picketed. BIG TOOMAI, a weathered mahout in working cloth, the son of Black Toomai, runs a hand along the elephant's leg. LITTLE TOOMAI, ten years old, four feet high, sun-bleached brown hair loose on his shoulders, one rag for clothes, stands up to his full height beside the great forefoot.

BIG TOOMAI
Yes. There is nothing that the Black Snake fears except me. He has seen three generations of us feed him and groom him, and he will live to see four.

LITTLE TOOMAI
He is afraid of me also.

He strides up, calls KALA NAG a fat old pig, and makes him lift his feet one after the other.

LITTLE TOOMAI
Wah! Thou art a big elephant. The Government may pay for elephants, but they belong to us mahouts. When thou art old, Kala Nag, some rich rajah will buy thee. Then thou wilt carry gold earrings and a gold howdah, and I shall sit on thy neck with a silver ankus, and men will run before us crying, "Room for the King's elephant!" That will be good, Kala Nag, but not so good as this hunting in the jungles.

BIG TOOMAI
Umph! Thou art a boy, and as wild as a buffalo-calf. This running up and down among the hills is not the best Government service. I am getting old, and I do not love wild elephants. Give me brick elephant lines, one stall to each elephant, and flat broad roads—instead of this come-and-go camping. Aha, the Cawnpore barracks were good.

LITTLE TOOMAI says nothing. His eyes are on the hills.

EXT. BRIDLE PATH IN THE HILLS - DAY

KALA NAG climbs a path only an elephant could take. LITTLE TOOMAI on his neck. Glimpses: wild elephants browsing miles away; pig and peacock bursting underfoot; warm rain smoking on the valleys; misty morning camps.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
What Little Toomai liked was the scramble, the drive, and the last night's rush when the elephants poured into the stockade like boulders in a landslide.

EXT. KEDDAH STOCKADE - NIGHT

The stockade quivers. Torches. Yells. Blank cartridges. LITTLE TOOMAI climbs a stockade post, hair flying, a goblin in the torch-light. Below, KALA NAG battles a wild tusker.

LITTLE TOOMAI
Mael, mael, Kala Nag! Dant do! Somalo! Somalo! Maro! Mar! Mind the post! Arre! Arre! Hai! Yai! Kya-a-ah!

Old elephant-catchers wipe sweat and nod up at him.

A rope end drops. LITTLE TOOMAI slides down between the elephants, throws the loose end up to a driver struggling with a kicking calf. KALA NAG catches the boy in his trunk and hands him up to BIG TOOMAI, who slaps him and puts him back on the post.

EXT. ELEPHANT CAMP CLEARING - DAY

Morning. BIG TOOMAI scolds LITTLE TOOMAI hard.

BIG TOOMAI
Are not good brick elephant lines and a little tent carrying enough, that thou must needs go elephant catching on thy own account, little worthless? Now those foolish hunters have spoken to Petersen Sahib of the matter.

LITTLE TOOMAI
What—what will happen?

BIG TOOMAI
Happen! The worst that can happen. Petersen Sahib is a madman. Else why should he go hunting these wild devils? He may even require thee to be an elephant catcher, to sleep in these fever-filled jungles, and at last to be trampled to death in the Keddah. Next week the catching is over, and we of the plains are sent back. But, son, I am angry that thou shouldst meddle in the business that belongs to these dirty Assamese jungle folk. Is the family of Toomai of the Elephants to be trodden underfoot in the dirt of a Keddah? Bad one! Wicked one! Worthless son! Go and wash Kala Nag and attend to his ears, and see that there are no thorns in his feet. Or else Petersen Sahib will surely catch thee and make thee a wild hunter. Bah! Shame! Go!

LITTLE TOOMAI goes without a word.

EXT. ELEPHANT PICKETS - DAY

LITTLE TOOMAI examines KALA NAG's feet, turns up the fringe of the huge right ear, works out a thorn.

LITTLE TOOMAI
No matter. They have said my name to Petersen Sahib, and perhaps—and perhaps—and perhaps—who knows? Hai! That is a big thorn that I have pulled out!

EXT. HILL PAY CAMP UNDER TREES - DAY

The season ending. Newly caught elephants in a restless line. A native clerk at a table under a tree pays wages. Catchers and hunters lean on guns and laugh at the plains drivers going away.

PETERSEN SAHIB, the head of the Keddah operations, lies along the back of his clever she-elephant PUDMINI. MACHUA APPA, the head tracker, speaks undertone to a friend as BIG TOOMAI and LITTLE TOOMAI approach the clerk.

MACHUA APPA
There goes one piece of good elephant stuff at least. 'Tis a pity to send that young jungle-cock to molt in the plains.

PETERSEN SAHIB turns on PUDMINI's back.

PETERSEN SAHIB
What is that? I did not know of a man among the plains-drivers who had wit enough to rope even a dead elephant.

MACHUA APPA
This is not a man, but a boy. He went into the Keddah at the last drive, and threw Barmao there the rope, when we were trying to get that young calf with the blotch on his shoulder away from his mother.

MACHUA APPA points. LITTLE TOOMAI bows to the earth.

PETERSEN SAHIB
He throw a rope? He is smaller than a picket-pin. Little one, what is thy name?

LITTLE TOOMAI is too frightened to speak. He signs. KALA NAG lifts him in his trunk and holds him level with PUDMINI's forehead before PETERSEN SAHIB. LITTLE TOOMAI covers his face with his hands.

PETERSEN SAHIB
(smiling under his mustache)
Oho! And why didst thou teach thy elephant that trick? Was it to help thee steal green corn from the roofs of the houses when the ears are ripe? Well, look up. Little man, there is nothing to fear. Look up and answer. What is thy name?

LITTLE TOOMAI
(whisper)
Little Toomai.

PETERSEN SAHIB
I have seen thee before. Next season thou shalt come again with Kala Nag and help in the Keddah. But now go and bathe Kala Nag. See, child, that he gets his food. And remember this: when next thou seest me, look me in the eyes and do not cover thy face. That is not the way of elephant-men.

He gives Little Toomai a coin and a silver-plated gun-barrel ankus. The camp stares.

That night the elephants grow restless. Kala Nag tugs at his picket. Little Toomai slips from his father's hut and climbs to the great neck.

EXT. JUNGLE PATH - NIGHT

KALA NAG breaks his picket-rope and walks into the forest. LITTLE TOOMAI clings on, half afraid, half wild with joy. Other elephants join from the darkness—wild and tame together—until a host moves under the stars toward the Garo hills.

EXT. ELEPHANT DANCE CLEARING - NIGHT

A great natural amphitheatre in the hills. Dozens—scores—of elephants gather. They stamp in solemn rhythm. The earth shakes. Dust rises white in moonlight. Trunks lift and swing. It is the dance no man is meant to see.

Little Toomai watches from Kala Nag's neck until dawn pales the peaks. Then the host breaks apart and the great beasts slip away into mist.

EXT. PETERSEN SAHIB'S CAMP - NIGHT

Little Toomai is brought back. The camp fires burn. Petersen Sahib and Machua Appa hear his story and see the dried mud of the dance-ground on Kala Nag's feet and the boy's.

The flames die down. Red light of the logs makes the picketed elephants look as though they have been dipped in blood.

MACHUA APPA leaps to his feet. He holds LITTLE TOOMAI high in the air above his head.

MACHUA APPA
Listen, my brothers. Listen, too, you my lords in the lines there, for I, Machua Appa, am speaking! This little one shall no more be called Little Toomai, but Toomai of the Elephants, as his great-grandfather was called before him. What never man has seen he has seen through the long night, and the favor of the elephant-folk and of the Gods of the Jungles is with him. He shall become a great tracker. He shall become greater than I, even I, Machua Appa! He shall follow the new trail, and the stale trail, and the mixed trail, with a clear eye! He shall take no harm in the Keddah when he runs under their bellies to rope the wild tuskers; and if he slips before the feet of the charging bull elephant, the bull elephant shall know who he is and shall not crush him. Aihai! my lords in the chains—

He whirls up the line of pickets.

MACHUA APPA
—here is the little one that has seen your dances in your hidden places,—the sight that never man saw! Give him honor, my lords! Salaam karo, my children. Make your salute to Toomai of the Elephants! Gunga Pershad, ahaa! Hira Guj, Birchi Guj, Kuttar Guj, ahaa! Pudmini,—thou hast seen him at the dance, and thou too, Kala Nag, my pearl among elephants!—ahaa! Together! To Toomai of the Elephants. Barrao!

At that last wild yell the whole line flings up their trunks till the tips touch their foreheads, and breaks out into the full salute—the crashing trumpet-peal that only the Viceroy of India hears, the Salaamut of the Keddah.

LITTLE TOOMAI—Toomai of the Elephants—stands small in the firelight beneath the lifted trunks, the blood-mark bright on his brow.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
But it was all for the sake of Little Toomai, who had seen what never man had seen before—the dance of the elephants at night and alone in the heart of the Garo hills!

INT. TOOMAI'S HUT - NIGHT

A low lamp. TOOMAI'S MOTHER rocks a sleeping baby against her breast. Outside, night insects. She sings soft and steady, the old song.

TOOMAI'S MOTHER
Shiv, who poured the harvest and made the winds to blow,
Sitting at the doorways of a day of long ago,
Gave to each his portion, food and toil and fate,
From the King upon the guddee to the Beggar at the gate.
All things made he—Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! He made all,—
Thorn for the camel, fodder for the kine,
And mother's heart for sleepy head, O little son of mine!

Wheat he gave to rich folk, millet to the poor,
Broken scraps for holy men that beg from door to door;
Battle to the tiger, carrion to the kite,
And rags and bones to wicked wolves without the wall at night.
Naught he found too lofty, none he saw too low—
Parbati beside him watched them come and go;
Thought to cheat her husband, turning Shiv to jest—
Stole the little grasshopper and hid it in her breast.
So she tricked him, Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! Turn and see.
Tall are the camels, heavy are the kine,
But this was Least of Little Things, O little son of mine!

When the dole was ended, laughingly she said,
"Master, of a million mouths, is not one unfed?"
Laughing, Shiv made answer, "All have had their part,
Even he, the little one, hidden 'neath thy heart."
From her breast she plucked it, Parbati the thief,
Saw the Least of Little Things gnawed a new-grown leaf!
Saw and feared and wondered, making prayer to Shiv,
Who hath surely given meat to all that live.
All things made he—Shiva the Preserver.
Mahadeo! Mahadeo! He made all,—
Thorn for the camel, fodder for the kine,
And mother's heart for sleepy head, O little son of mine!

She kisses the baby's hair. The lamp gutters.

EXT. RAWAL PINDI CAMP - NIGHT

Rain. A vast military camp of thirty thousand men—camels, elephants, horses, bullocks, and mules—gathered for review before the Viceroy and the visiting Amir of Afghanistan. Mud everywhere. Tent ropes. Heel-ropes. Lamps drowned in drizzle.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It had been raining heavily for one whole month—raining on a camp of thirty thousand men and thousands of camels, elephants, horses, bullocks, and mules all gathered together at a place called Rawal Pindi, to be reviewed by the Viceroy of India. He was receiving a visit from the Amir of Afghanistan—a wild king of a very wild country.

Savage Central Asian horses stampede through the dark. Camels break loose and blunder over tent-ropes.

A man shoves his head into a tent.

CAMP MAN
Get out, quick! They're coming! My tent's gone!

NARRATOR—a man in boots and waterproof—scrambles out into the slush. Little VIXEN, a fox terrier, darts out the other side.

A roaring, grunting, bubbling. The tent caves in as the pole snaps and dances like a mad ghost—a camel has blundered into it.

NARRATOR laughs once, wet and angry, then runs on through the mud, out of sight of the camp lights.

EXT. ARTILLERY LINES - NIGHT

NARRATOR falls over the tail-end of a gun. Cannon stacked for the night. He spreads his waterproof over a muzzle, makes a wigwam of rammers, and lies along the tail of another gun. Rain ticks on iron.

A jingle of harness. A grunt. BILLY, a screw-gun mule, passes shaking wet ears—straps, rings, and chains rattling on his saddle-pad.

Behind him, a BAGGAGE CAMEL with big soft feet squelching in the mud, neck bobbing like a strayed hen's.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
What shall I do? Where shall I go? I have fought with a white thing that waved, and it took a stick and hit me on the neck. Shall we run on?

BILLY
Oh, it was you, you and your friends, that have been disturbing the camp? All right. You'll be beaten for this in the morning. But I may as well give you something on account now.

Harness jingles. Billy backs and catches the camel two kicks in the ribs that ring like a drum.

BILLY
Another time you'll know better than to run through a mule battery at night, shouting "Thieves and fire!" Sit down, and keep your silly neck quiet.

The camel doubles up camel-fashion and sits down whimpering.

A regular beat of hoofs. TROOP-HORSE—big, steady, Number Fifteen, E troop, Ninth Lancers—canters up as though on parade, jumps a gun-tail, and lands close to Billy.

TROOP-HORSE
It's disgraceful. Those camels have racketed through our lines again—the third time this week. How's a horse to keep his condition if he isn't allowed to sleep. Who's here?

BILLY
I'm the breech-piece mule of number two gun of the First Screw Battery, and the other's one of your friends. He's waked me up too. Who are you?

TROOP-HORSE
Number Fifteen, E troop, Ninth Lancers—Dick Cunliffe's horse. Stand over a little, there.

BILLY
Oh, beg your pardon. It's too dark to see much. Aren't these camels too sickening for anything? I walked out of my lines to get a little peace and quiet here.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
(humbly)
My lords, we dreamed bad dreams in the night, and we were very much afraid. I am only a baggage camel of the 39th Native Infantry, and I am not as brave as you are, my lords.

BILLY
Then why didn't you stay and carry baggage for the 39th Native Infantry, instead of running all round the camp?

BAGGAGE CAMEL
They were such very bad dreams. I am sorry. Listen! What is that? Shall we run on again?

BILLY
Sit down, or you'll snap your long stick-legs between the guns.

Billy cocks one ear.

BILLY
Bullocks! Gun bullocks. On my word, you and your friends have waked the camp very thoroughly. It takes a good deal of prodding to put up a gun-bullock.

A chain drags. A yoke of great sulky white GUN BULLOCKS—the seventh yoke of the first gun of the Big Gun Battery—come shouldering along. Almost stepping on the chain, YOUNG MULE calls wildly.

YOUNG MULE
Billy! Billy!

BILLY
(to Troop-Horse)
That's one of our recruits. He's calling for me. Here, youngster, stop squealing. The dark never hurt anybody yet.

The gun-bullocks lie down together and chew the cud. Young Mule huddles close to Billy.

YOUNG MULE
Things! Fearful and horrible, Billy! They came into our lines while we were asleep. D'you think they'll kill us?

BILLY
I've a very great mind to give you a number-one kicking. The idea of a fourteen-hand mule with your training disgracing the battery before this gentleman!

TROOP-HORSE
Gently, gently! Remember they are always like this to begin with. The first time I ever saw a man (it was in Australia when I was a three-year-old) I ran for half a day, and if I'd seen a camel, I should have been running still.

BILLY
True enough. Before I was three I thought the rattling of a harness was the end of the world. Who's that coming now?

A deep soft step. TWO TAME ELEPHANTS loom out of the rain—one with a driver's seat, one free. The nearer is the great gun-elephant of the battery.

GUN ELEPHANT
Peace, friends. We also could not sleep for the shouting of the camels. Is it true that the Amir comes tomorrow and we shall all be reviewed?

TROOP-HORSE
True enough. And a native officer told me the Viceroy will be there, and the guns will fire, and there will be a great noise.

YOUNG MULE
Will there—will there be any of those things that make fire?

BILLY
Of course there will. Screw-guns of the First Battery. You'll stand next me. Don't be afraid.

BAGGAGE CAMEL
And shall we all be killed?

GUN BULLOCK
(deep and slow)
We have heard this talk before. There is nothing to kill. When the fire comes we stand still. That is the Law.

TROOP-HORSE
Exactly. Stand still and obey. That is all that is asked of any of us.

From far off in the wet dark, a jackal's howl—then another. Vixen the terrier bristles under the waterproof.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And so they talked until the rain lessened and the first gray showed over the guns. Each beast in his place—mule and horse, bullock and camel and elephant—bound by the same service, the same wet night, and the same Law that is older than any regiment: stand still, and obey, and carry the day's load until the day's end.

EXT. RAWAL PINDI PARADE GROUND - DAY

Sun after rain. Thirty thousand men and beasts drawn up for the great review. Dust and glitter. The Amir and the Viceroy pass. Guns speak. Elephants salaam. Mules stand like rock. Far beyond the parade, the hills hold their silence—and somewhere in those hills the Free People still keep the Jungle Law.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Now these are the Laws of the Jungle, and many and mighty are they; but the head and the hoof of the Law and the haunch and the hump is—Obey!

FADE OUT.

THE END
